1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ALLOW A JUDGE TO ISSUE A PERMANENT NO CONTACT ORDER
3 AGAINST A DEFENDANT CONVICTED OF CERTAIN VIOLENT OFFENSES AND
4 TO PROVIDE THAT IT IS FELONY CHILD ABUSE FOR ANY PERSON PROVIDING
5 CARE TO OR SUPERVISION OF A CHILD LESS THAN SIXTEEN YEARS OF AGE TO
6 COMMIT OR ALLOW THE COMMISSION OF A SEXUAL ACT UPON THE CHILD.
7 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
8
9 PART I. ALLOWING JUDGE TO ISSUE A PERMANENT NO CONTACT ORDER
10 AGAINST A DEFENDANT CONVICTED OF CERTAIN VIOLENT OFFENSES
11 SECTION 1.(a) Article 81D of Chapter 15A of the General Statutes reads as
12 rewritten:
13 "Article 81D.
14 "Permanent No Contact Order Against Convicted Sex Violent Offender.
15 "§ 15A-1340.50. Permanent no contact order prohibiting future contact by convicted sex
16 violent offender with crime victim.
17 (a) The following definitions apply in this Article:
18 (1) Permanent no contact order. – A permanent injunction that prohibits any
19 contact by a defendant with the victim of the sex violent offense for which the
20 defendant is convicted. convicted, with the victim's immediate family, or both.
21 The duration of the injunction is the lifetime of the defendant.
22 (2) Sex offense. – Any criminal offense that requires registration under Article
23 27A of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes.
24 (3) Victim. – The person against whom the sex violent offense was committed.
25 (4) Violent offense. – Any of the following:
26 a. A criminal offense that requires registration under Article 27A of
27 Chapter 14 of the General Statutes.
28 b. A Class A through G felony that is not otherwise covered under
29 sub-subdivision a. of this subdivision.
30 c. An offense under subsection (b) of G.S. 14-32.4.
31 (b) When sentencing a defendant convicted of a sex violent offense, the judge, at the
32 request of the district attorney, shall determine whether to issue a permanent no contact order.
33 The judge shall order the defendant to show cause why a permanent no contact order shall not be
34 issued and shall hold a show cause hearing as part of the sentencing procedures for the defendant.
35 (c) The victim victim, the victim's immediate family, or both shall have a right to be heard
36 at the show cause hearing.
*H182-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 …
2 (e) At the conclusion of the show cause hearing the judge shall enter a finding for or
3 against the defendant. If the judge determines that reasonable grounds exist for the victim victim,
4 the victim's immediate family, or both to fear any future contact with the defendant, the judge
5 shall issue the permanent no contact order. The judge shall enter written findings of fact and the
6 grounds on which the permanent no contact order is issued. issued. If any member of the victim's
7 immediate family is included in the permanent no contact order, they must be specifically
8 identified. The no contact order shall be incorporated into the judgment imposing the sentence
9 on the defendant for the conviction of the sex violent offense.
10 (f) The court may grant one or more of the following forms of relief in a permanent no
11 contact order under this Article:
12 (1) Order the defendant not to threaten, visit, assault, molest, or otherwise
13 interfere with the victim.victim, the victim's immediate family, or both.
14 (2) Order the defendant not to follow the victim, the victim's immediate family,
15 or both, including at the victim's each individual's workplace.
16 (3) Order the defendant not to harass the victim.victim, the victim's immediate
17 family, or both.
18 (4) Order the defendant not to abuse or injure the victim.victim, the victim's
19 immediate family, or both.
20 (5) Order the defendant not to contact the victim victim, the victim's immediate
21 family, or both by telephone, written communication, or electronic means.
22 (6) Order the defendant to refrain from entering or remaining present at the
23 victim's residence, school, place of employment, school, or place of
24 employment of the victim, the victim's immediate family, or both, or other
25 specified places at times when the victim victim, the victim's immediate
26 family, or both are present.
27 (7) Order other relief deemed necessary and appropriate by the court.
28 …
29 (h) At any time after the issuance of the order, the State, at the request of the victim, or
30 the defendant may make a motion to rescind or modify the permanent no contact order. If the
31 court determines that reasonable grounds for the victim victim, the victim's immediate family, or
32 both to fear any future contact with the defendant no longer exist, the court may rescind or modify
33 the permanent no contact order.
34 …."
35 SECTION 1.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to
36 offenses committed on or after that date.
37
38 PART II. CLARIFYING CHANGES TO FELONY CHILD ABUSE LAWS
39 SECTION 2.(a) G.S. 14-318.4 reads as rewritten:
40 "§ 14-318.4. Child abuse a felony.
41 (a) A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than 16
42 years of age who intentionally inflicts any serious physical injury upon or to the child or who
43 intentionally commits an assault upon the child which results in any serious physical injury to
44 the child is guilty of a Class D felony, except as otherwise provided in subsection (a3) of this
45 section.
46 (a1) Any A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than
47 16 years of age, or any other person providing care to or supervision of the child, age who
48 commits, permits, or encourages any act of prostitution with or by the child is guilty of child
49 abuse and shall be punished as a Class D felon.
Page 2 House Bill 182-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (a2) Any A parent or legal guardian of any other person providing care to or supervision
2 of a child less than 16 years of age who commits or allows the commission of any sexual act
3 upon the child is guilty of a Class D felony.
4 (a3) A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than 16
5 years of age who intentionally inflicts any serious bodily injury to the child or who intentionally
6 commits an assault upon the child which results in any serious bodily injury to the child, or which
7 results in permanent or protracted loss or impairment of any mental or emotional function of the
8 child, is guilty of a Class B2 felony.
9 (a4) A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than 16
10 years of age who, for the purpose of causing fear, emotional injury, or deriving sexual
11 gratification, intentionally and routinely (i) inflicts physical injury on that child and (ii) deprives
12 that child of necessary food, clothing, shelter, or proper physical care is guilty of a Class B2
13 felony.
14 (a4)(a5) A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than
15 16 years of age whose willful act or grossly negligent omission in the care of the child shows a
16 reckless disregard for human life is guilty of a Class E felony if the act or omission results in
17 serious bodily injury to the child.
18 (a5)(a7) A parent or any other person providing care to or supervision of a child less than
19 16 years of age whose willful act or grossly negligent omission in the care of the child shows a
20 reckless disregard for human life is guilty of a Class G felony if the act or omission results in
21 serious physical injury to the child.
22 (a6) For purposes of this section, a "grossly negligent omission" in providing care to or
23 supervision of a child includes the failure to report a child as missing to law enforcement as
24 provided in G.S. 14-318.5(b).
25 (b) The felony of child abuse is an offense additional to other civil and criminal
26 provisions and is not intended to repeal or preclude any other sanctions or remedies.
27 (c) Abandonment of an infant less than seven days of age pursuant to G.S. 14-322.3 may
28 be treated as a mitigating factor in sentencing for a conviction under this section involving that
29 infant.
30 (d) The following definitions apply in this section:
31 (1) Grossly negligent omission. – In the context of providing care to or
32 supervision of a child, this term includes the failure to report a child as missing
33 to law enforcement as provided in G.S. 14-318.5(b).
34 (2) Serious bodily injury. – Bodily injury that creates a substantial risk of death
35 or that causes serious permanent disfigurement, coma, a permanent or
36 protracted condition that causes extreme pain, or permanent or protracted loss
37 or impairment of the function of any bodily member or organ, or that results
38 in prolonged hospitalization.
39 (2)(3) Serious physical injury. – Physical injury that causes great pain and suffering.
40 The term includes serious mental injury."
41 SECTION 2.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to
42 offenses committed on or after that date.
43
44 PART III. SAVINGS CLAUSE & EFFECTIVE DATE
45 SECTION 3.(a) Prosecutions for offenses committed before the effective date of
46 this act are not abated or affected by this act, and the statutes that would be applicable but for
47 this act remain applicable to those prosecutions.
48 SECTION 3.(b) Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
49 law.
